commitResults.messageBody:
Add the features for a skeletal program as specificed in Level-1

Let's
* Make the program greet the user
* Make the program echo commands
* Make the program exit with the 'bye' command

See below for more details.
https://nus-cs2103-ay2021s1.github.io/website/schedule/week2/project.html

commitResults.messageTitle: Commands: Use switch-case instead of if statements
commitResults.messageBody:
The program checks for commands in user input using
if statements.

Adding more commands will make the code harder to
read.

Let's use switch case statements to check for commands
instead of if statements

The program echos user input.

The program should remember user input and display them
back to the user when requested.

Let's
* Add a 'list' command that lists previous commands
* Remember all input that is not 'list' and 'bye'

See below for more information
https://nus-cs2103-ay2021s1.github.io/website/schedule/week2/project.html

commitResults.messageTitle: Use a class to represent tasks
commitResults.messageBody:
Tasks are represented as strings.

Tasks can contain other properties such as completion status.
Using classes will allow simpler implementation of these
properties.

Let's
* Create a Task class
* Change existing code to use the Task class
* Add an additional 'isDone' property to track the completion

* Task list starts at 0
* Entire user input is checked to match a command

* Task list should start at 1 for natural counting
* Future commands may require additional parameters,
  so only the first word should be checked, with the
  rest used as parameters

Let's
* Start counting task list from 1
* Only check first word of user input for matching
  command

Bug: Only first word of task is stored as task description

Let's
* Add a 'done' command
* Add the ability to mark tasks as done
* Fix the above bug

See below for more information
https://nus-cs2103-ay2021s1.github.io/website/schedule/week2/project.html

Add todo, event and deadline classes in anticipation
for the Level-4 requirements.

Let's add classes for todo, events and deadlines that
inherit from the Task class

Use inheritance to reduce code duplication, such as for
printing tasks and marking as done

Let's
* Add support for ToDos
* Add support for Deadlines
* Add support for Events

Let's
* Add automated testing using I/O redirection

Implement the mimimal requirements for error handling

Let's
* Create a DukeException class to encapsulate error data
* Extract command processing logic to its own function to
  allow for exceptions
* Implement error handling for missing todo descriptions
* Implement error hanlding for unknown commands
* Update tests to check for error handling

See below for more information
https://nus-cs2103-ay2021s1.github.io/website/schedule/week2/project.html

Bug: Program does not exit properly after 'bye'
command is given.

Let's
* Add support for deleting tasks from the list
* Update tests to check new features
* Fix the above bug

See below for more information
https://nus-cs2103-ay2021s1.github.io/website/schedule/week2/project.html

commitResults.messageTitle: Commands: Use enums instead of strings
commitResults.messageBody:
Commands are processed as strings directly from user input

Commands can be handled in a case insensitive way using enums

Let's convert the user input to an enum before processing

Task data is not saved to hard disk, so data is
lost when the user quits and restarts the program

A save and load feature allows user data to
persist through program runs.

Let's
* add a DataManager class to manage file io
* save task data when the user updates the
  task list
* load the saved task data when the program
  starts

Represent dates as LocalDate instead of String

Let's
* store date data as LocalDate objects instead of string
* format date outputs according to locale
* accept date inputs in the format: "yyyy-mm-dd"

Dates are parsed and formatted as strings instead of LocalDate objects

Let's parse and format dates as LocalDate objects

All task list features are handled in the main program.
(e.g. adding, deleting, updating)

Extracting these features to their own object will make
it easier to manage in the future.

Let's
* Extract task list related features to a TaskList class
* Update save/load to work with the new class

User I/O is being handled in the main program

Extracting user I/O to its own class will make
it easier to manage

Let's create anew UIManager class to handle
user I/O

Let's
* Add test for displaying startup message
* Add test for printing in window
* Add test for creating todo

Let's give users a way to find a task by
searching for a keyword

Code style is inconsistent. Some lines
are too long.

Code should follow the established
conventions to make it easier to read.

Lets clean up areas that are not following
the code convention.
